!! Hello
    Look around your apartment, and you'll see many rocks.  From chalk's porous limestone to the smooth slate
    of blackboards, *rocks* --- that is, solid mineral aggregates --- abound.  Now scan beyond your window: notice a
    passerby slipping on compacted snow; observe the machinations of an empire built on the energy of coal; imagine
    the obsidian arrowheads veiled from view by grass and soil and millenia.  Rocks are Nature's building blocks.

    But rocks are not static: in their constant flows and fluxes they are the very scroll on which Nature writes her
    history.  Hold a rock, and feel the weight of its age, the wisdom of its dimpled skin.  Its molecules may well have
    witnessed the birth of life itself.  In their eternal dance of deposition and erosion, those molecules endure the
    cruel pressures of inner earth, rising only as tortured tectonic plates screech and wrestle and belch their innards
    out.  As exiles, they drift from dune to dune across ancient deserts.  Some even dissolve in animal stomachs only
    to reincarnate as the sheen of a beautiful shell.  *Geology*, then, distinguishes itself in the pace and subtle
    violence of the processes it studies.

    These notes tour the many facets of rocks and their history.  Assuming no background, we build from the basics:
    quantum field theory to explain the material properties of rock, cosmology to describe the 
    origins of rock, neo darwinian theory to understand the interactions of rock and life, and fluid dynamics to model
    the climate that so affects surface geology.  From here, we briefly describe a diverse set of processes such as the
    saltation of sand and the life cycle of hoodoos.  We finally survey two major applications of rocks: the
    construction of Turing-complete machines from silicon and rock-based survival skills.

    All said, geology is a central science.  If Aristotle's earth tended to sink below water, air, and fire, so too 
    does geology tend to motivate the more applied sciences of physics, chemistry, and biology.  But to call geology
    impractical is to err.  While our technical preparations may petrify the uninitiated, just think, dear reader,
    whenever you waver, of the dominion of human above rock in that grandest of engineering triumphs: Khufu's pyramid.  
    Oriented thus with curiosity and pluck, let us climb our own pyramid.  We begin at the beginning: with field
    theory.

